         <abstract>
            <p>Analysis of the performance of three types of black-owned financial institutions (life insurance companies, savings and loan associations, and commercial banks) discloses that all three have not done nearly as well as comparable white institutions. While the reasons vary among the types of institutions, a pattern of weakness is common to all three: a combination of high expenses, low profit margins, and weak levels of capitalization.</p>
         </abstract>
